/* CISA :: content/quiz1.js — CISA Domain 1 question bank (100 items). */
window.CISA = window.CISA || {}; CISA.questions = CISA.questions || [];
CISA.questions.push.apply(CISA.questions, [
{"id":"D1-001","domain":1,"obj":"1A1","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is preparing an engagement. Which ISACA source provides the mandatory professional requirements the auditor MUST follow?","options":["IS Audit and Assurance Guidelines","IS Audit and Assurance Tools and Techniques","The audit committee charter","IS Audit and Assurance Standards"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>IS Audit and Assurance Standards</strong> — within ITAF, the Standards are mandatory and define the required level of performance and reporting an IS auditor must meet.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>IS Audit and Assurance Guidelines</b>: guidelines provide guidance on applying the standards but are not mandatory.</span><span class='qd'><b>IS Audit and Assurance Tools and Techniques</b>: these give practical examples and are the least authoritative, non-mandatory layer of ITAF.</span><span class='qd'><b>The audit committee charter</b>: it governs the audit function's authority within the organization, not ISACA's mandatory professional requirements.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-002","domain":1,"obj":"1A1","diff":"medium","q":"ISACA's framework that organizes IS audit and assurance standards, guidelines, and tools/techniques is known as:","options":["COBIT","ITAF","COSO","ISO 27001"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>ITAF</strong> — the Information Technology Assurance Framework is ISACA's comprehensive model that houses the mandatory standards, the guidelines, and the tools and techniques for IS assurance work.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>COBIT</b>: COBIT is a governance and management framework for enterprise IT, not the structure for audit standards.</span><span class='qd'><b>COSO</b>: COSO is an internal-control and enterprise-risk framework, not ISACA's assurance framework.</span><span class='qd'><b>ISO 27001</b>: ISO 27001 specifies requirements for an information security management system, not IS audit standards.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-003","domain":1,"obj":"1A1","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor discovers that a close friend manages the department under audit. Under the ISACA Code of Professional Ethics, the auditor should FIRST:","options":["Continue the audit but document the relationship in the workpapers","Disclose the relationship to audit management so independence can be assessed","Withdraw silently from the engagement","Ask the friend to recuse himself from the department"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Disclose the relationship to audit management so independence can be assessed</strong> — the Code requires maintaining independence and objectivity; disclosing a potential impairment lets management decide on reassignment or safeguards.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Continue the audit but document the relationship in the workpapers</b>: documentation alone does not resolve the impairment to objectivity that must be evaluated by management first.</span><span class='qd'><b>Withdraw silently from the engagement</b>: leaving without disclosure hides the reason and prevents management from managing the risk properly.</span><span class='qd'><b>Ask the friend to recuse himself from the department</b>: the auditee cannot be reassigned to fix the auditor's own independence conflict.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-004","domain":1,"obj":"1A1","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is asked to design and then audit the same access-control solution. This situation MOST directly threatens the auditor's:","options":["Due professional care","Objectivity","Technical competence","Confidentiality"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Objectivity</strong> — auditing one's own work creates a self-review threat, impairing the impartiality the auditor must maintain when forming conclusions.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Due professional care</b>: due care concerns the diligence applied, not the independence conflict of reviewing self-designed work.</span><span class='qd'><b>Technical competence</b>: competence is about skill and knowledge, which are not what this dual role compromises.</span><span class='qd'><b>Confidentiality</b>: confidentiality relates to protecting information, which is not the issue when self-reviewing a design.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-005","domain":1,"obj":"1A1","diff":"medium","q":"Which document formally grants the IS audit function its authority, scope, and right of access to records and staff?","options":["The audit charter","The audit engagement letter","The annual audit plan","The audit program"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>The audit charter</strong> — approved by the board or audit committee, the charter establishes the audit function's purpose, authority, responsibility, and right of access across the organization.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The audit engagement letter</b>: an engagement letter documents the terms of a single assignment, not the function's overarching mandate.</span><span class='qd'><b>The annual audit plan</b>: the plan lists what will be audited in a period, but derives its authority from the charter.</span><span class='qd'><b>The audit program</b>: the program is the detailed set of procedures for one engagement, not a grant of authority.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-006","domain":1,"obj":"1A1","diff":"hard","q":"An internal IS auditor reports functionally to the CFO and administratively to the CIO. To BEST preserve independence, the auditor's functional reporting line should be changed to the:","options":["Chief information officer","Audit committee of the board","Chief financial officer","Head of the compliance department"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Audit committee of the board</strong> — a functional reporting line to the audit committee places the audit function above operational management, preserving organizational independence.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Chief information officer</b>: the CIO owns much of the IT being audited, so reporting to the CIO creates a direct independence conflict.</span><span class='qd'><b>Chief financial officer</b>: the CFO manages areas subject to audit and cannot provide the independent oversight the audit committee does.</span><span class='qd'><b>Head of the compliance department</b>: compliance is itself an operational function that may be audited, so it is not an independent reporting line.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-007","domain":1,"obj":"1A1","diff":"easy","q":"Under the ISACA Code of Professional Ethics, an IS auditor who lacks the skills for a specialized cloud engagement should:","options":["Proceed and learn the technology during fieldwork","Rely entirely on management's representations","Limit the scope silently to areas already understood","Decline the engagement or arrange for competent assistance"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Decline the engagement or arrange for competent assistance</strong> — the Code requires performing work only where competence exists; obtaining qualified assistance upholds professional competence and due care.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Proceed and learn the technology during fieldwork</b>: performing an engagement without adequate competence risks flawed conclusions and violates the ethics code.</span><span class='qd'><b>Rely entirely on management's representations</b>: representations are not sufficient evidence and do not substitute for auditor competence.</span><span class='qd'><b>Limit the scope silently to areas already understood</b>: a silent scope reduction misleads stakeholders and breaches the duty of full disclosure.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-008","domain":1,"obj":"1A1","diff":"medium","q":"Which of the following is the PRIMARY purpose of ISACA's IS Audit and Assurance Guidelines?","options":["To mandate minimum audit performance requirements","To certify audit software tools","To provide guidance on how to apply the standards","To replace the audit charter"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>To provide guidance on how to apply the standards</strong> — guidelines assist the auditor in applying the mandatory standards and exercising professional judgment, but are not themselves mandatory.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>To mandate minimum audit performance requirements</b>: that is the role of the standards, which are mandatory, not the guidelines.</span><span class='qd'><b>To certify audit software tools</b>: guidelines do not certify tools; they explain how to apply standards.</span><span class='qd'><b>To replace the audit charter</b>: the charter grants authority and is unrelated to the advisory role of guidelines.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-009","domain":1,"obj":"1A1","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor is offered a substantial gift by an auditee shortly before issuing the final report. The MOST appropriate action is to:","options":["Accept it since fieldwork is already complete","Accept it and disclose it only if the report is favorable","Decline the gift and report the offer per the ethics policy","Return it privately without informing anyone"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Decline the gift and report the offer per the ethics policy</strong> — accepting a gift creates an appearance of impaired objectivity; declining and reporting the offer preserves independence in fact and appearance.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Accept it since fieldwork is already complete</b>: the report is not yet issued and the gift can still be seen to influence conclusions and follow-up.</span><span class='qd'><b>Accept it and disclose it only if the report is favorable</b>: conditional disclosure still compromises objectivity and hides a conflict.</span><span class='qd'><b>Return it privately without informing anyone</b>: failing to report the offer prevents management from addressing a potential integrity concern.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-010","domain":1,"obj":"1A1","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor notices during a payroll audit evidence of a possible fraud unrelated to the audit's scope. Under the Code of Professional Ethics, the auditor should:","options":["Ignore it because it is outside the agreed scope","Investigate it personally and confront the suspect","Wait until the next scheduled audit to raise it","Report it to the appropriate parties through proper channels"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Report it to the appropriate parties through proper channels</strong> — the Code requires disclosing significant matters; suspected fraud must be communicated to those charged with governance regardless of the original scope.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Ignore it because it is outside the agreed scope</b>: ethics and professional responsibility require reporting significant irregularities discovered during the work.</span><span class='qd'><b>Investigate it personally and confront the suspect</b>: independent investigation and confrontation exceed the auditor's role and may compromise a formal inquiry.</span><span class='qd'><b>Wait until the next scheduled audit to raise it</b>: delay allows harm to continue and violates the duty of timely disclosure.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-011","domain":1,"obj":"1A2","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is testing whether the organization adheres to its own password policy and to applicable regulations. This type of audit is BEST described as a:","options":["Substantive audit","Forensic audit","Compliance audit","Financial audit"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Compliance audit</strong> — a compliance audit determines whether controls and activities conform to policies, standards, laws, or regulations.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Substantive audit</b>: substantive testing verifies the accuracy and completeness of data or balances, not adherence to a policy.</span><span class='qd'><b>Forensic audit</b>: a forensic audit gathers evidence of fraud or crime for legal proceedings, which is not the objective here.</span><span class='qd'><b>Financial audit</b>: a financial audit expresses an opinion on financial statements, not on policy conformity.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-012","domain":1,"obj":"1A2","diff":"easy","q":"Management requests an audit that combines review of both IT general controls and the related financial application controls in a single engagement. This is MOST accurately called an:","options":["Integrated audit","Operational audit","Forensic audit","Pre-implementation review"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Integrated audit</strong> — an integrated audit combines financial, operational, and IS control testing so business-process and IT controls are evaluated together.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Operational audit</b>: an operational audit focuses on efficiency and effectiveness of operations, not the combined financial-plus-IT control assessment described.</span><span class='qd'><b>Forensic audit</b>: a forensic audit investigates suspected fraud for legal use, which is not requested here.</span><span class='qd'><b>Pre-implementation review</b>: this evaluates a system before go-live, not existing combined controls.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-013","domain":1,"obj":"1A2","diff":"medium","q":"An organization asks an IS auditor to evaluate the efficiency and effectiveness of its help-desk operations. This engagement is a(n):","options":["Compliance audit","Financial audit","SOC 1 examination","Operational audit"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Operational audit</strong> — operational audits assess how efficiently and effectively a function uses its resources to achieve objectives.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Compliance audit</b>: compliance work checks conformity to rules, not operational efficiency and effectiveness.</span><span class='qd'><b>Financial audit</b>: a financial audit opines on financial statement fairness, not help-desk performance.</span><span class='qd'><b>SOC 1 examination</b>: a SOC 1 report addresses controls relevant to user entities' financial reporting at a service organization, not internal help-desk efficiency.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-014","domain":1,"obj":"1A2","diff":"hard","q":"A user organization relies on a cloud provider and wants independent assurance over the design and operating effectiveness of the provider's security controls over a period. The MOST relevant report to request is a:","options":["SOC 1 Type 1 report","SOC 2 Type 2 report","SOC 3 general-use report","A bridge letter"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>SOC 2 Type 2 report</strong> — a SOC 2 Type 2 covers security and other trust services criteria and tests operating effectiveness over a period, giving detailed independent assurance to user entities.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>SOC 1 Type 1 report</b>: SOC 1 addresses controls over financial reporting, and Type 1 covers only design at a point in time, not operating effectiveness over a period.</span><span class='qd'><b>SOC 3 general-use report</b>: SOC 3 is a summary, general-use report lacking the detailed control descriptions and test results needed for assurance evaluation.</span><span class='qd'><b>A bridge letter</b>: a bridge letter only covers the gap between a report period and a later date and is not an examination itself.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-015","domain":1,"obj":"1A2","diff":"easy","q":"Which type of audit is specifically designed to gather and preserve evidence suitable for use in a court of law?","options":["Operational audit","Compliance audit","Financial audit","Forensic audit"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Forensic audit</strong> — a forensic audit collects, preserves, and analyzes evidence with the chain of custody and rigor needed for legal proceedings.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Operational audit</b>: it evaluates efficiency and effectiveness, not legal evidence.</span><span class='qd'><b>Compliance audit</b>: it verifies adherence to rules, without the evidentiary preservation focus of forensics.</span><span class='qd'><b>Financial audit</b>: it opines on financial statements rather than preparing court-admissible evidence.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-016","domain":1,"obj":"1A2","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is engaged to review a new ERP system before it goes live so that control weaknesses can be corrected inexpensively. This is a:","options":["Post-implementation review","Pre-implementation review","Compliance audit","Forensic audit"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Pre-implementation review</strong> — reviewing a system before go-live lets the auditor identify control gaps while they are cheapest to fix, before the system is in production.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Post-implementation review</b>: this occurs after go-live to assess whether objectives were met, which is not the timing described.</span><span class='qd'><b>Compliance audit</b>: compliance testing checks conformity to rules rather than pre-deployment control design.</span><span class='qd'><b>Forensic audit</b>: forensic work targets fraud evidence, which is unrelated to a pre-go-live control review.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-017","domain":1,"obj":"1A2","diff":"hard","q":"The PRIMARY difference between compliance testing and substantive testing is that compliance testing:","options":["Confirms the monetary accuracy of balances","Is always performed using CAATs","Evaluates whether controls are operating as designed","Is only used in forensic engagements"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Evaluates whether controls are operating as designed</strong> — compliance testing determines whether controls exist and function, while substantive testing verifies the accuracy and completeness of the underlying data.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Confirms the monetary accuracy of balances</b>: verifying monetary accuracy is the goal of substantive testing, not compliance testing.</span><span class='qd'><b>Is always performed using CAATs</b>: compliance tests can be manual or automated; CAAT use is not a defining trait.</span><span class='qd'><b>Is only used in forensic engagements</b>: compliance testing is used broadly across audit types, not exclusively in forensics.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-018","domain":1,"obj":"1A2","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor finds that control-testing results are poor and controls appear unreliable. The auditor should MOST appropriately respond by:","options":["Reducing the extent of substantive testing","Omitting substantive testing entirely","Increasing the extent of substantive testing","Issuing an unqualified opinion immediately"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Increasing the extent of substantive testing</strong> — when controls are weak, the auditor cannot rely on them and must expand substantive procedures to obtain sufficient assurance about the data.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Reducing the extent of substantive testing</b>: reduction is justified only when controls are strong and can be relied upon, which is the opposite here.</span><span class='qd'><b>Omitting substantive testing entirely</b>: with unreliable controls, omitting substantive work would leave the auditor without adequate evidence.</span><span class='qd'><b>Issuing an unqualified opinion immediately</b>: an opinion cannot be issued before obtaining sufficient evidence in the face of control weaknesses.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-019","domain":1,"obj":"1A2","diff":"medium","q":"Which engagement provides the LOWEST level of assurance and typically results in a conclusion rather than an opinion?","options":["A financial statement audit","A SOC 2 Type 2 examination","A review engagement","A forensic investigation"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>A review engagement</strong> — a review provides limited (negative) assurance through inquiry and analytical procedures, expressing a conclusion rather than the positive opinion of a full audit.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A financial statement audit</b>: an audit provides reasonable assurance and a positive opinion, a higher level than a review.</span><span class='qd'><b>A SOC 2 Type 2 examination</b>: an examination provides reasonable assurance with an opinion on control effectiveness.</span><span class='qd'><b>A forensic investigation</b>: forensic work gathers evidence for legal purposes and is not on the assurance-level continuum.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-020","domain":1,"obj":"1A2","diff":"easy","q":"A third-party service organization provides an assurance report describing its controls and an auditor's opinion for use by its customers. This is generally a:","options":["Penetration test report","SOC report","Vulnerability scan report","Business impact analysis"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>SOC report</strong> — a System and Organization Controls report describes a service organization's controls and includes an independent auditor's opinion for user entities.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Penetration test report</b>: a pen test documents exploited vulnerabilities, not a formal controls opinion for customers.</span><span class='qd'><b>Vulnerability scan report</b>: a scan lists technical weaknesses without an assurance opinion on controls.</span><span class='qd'><b>Business impact analysis</b>: a BIA assesses the impact of disruptions and is unrelated to third-party control assurance.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-021","domain":1,"obj":"1A3","diff":"medium","q":"The inventory of all auditable entities, processes, and systems that could be included in the audit plan is known as the:","options":["Audit charter","Audit program","Audit opinion","Audit universe"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Audit universe</strong> — the audit universe is the complete list of potential audit subjects from which the risk-based plan selects engagements.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Audit charter</b>: the charter grants the function its authority, not the inventory of auditable entities.</span><span class='qd'><b>Audit program</b>: the program lists procedures for one engagement, not the population of all auditable areas.</span><span class='qd'><b>Audit opinion</b>: the opinion is the conclusion issued after an audit, not a planning inventory.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-022","domain":1,"obj":"1A3","diff":"hard","q":"When developing a risk-based annual audit plan, the IS auditor should give the HIGHEST priority to areas that:","options":["Are easiest to audit with available staff","Were audited most recently","Are requested by the IT department","Have the highest combined risk and impact to the organization"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Have the highest combined risk and impact to the organization</strong> — risk-based planning allocates limited audit resources to the areas posing the greatest risk to organizational objectives.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Are easiest to audit with available staff</b>: convenience does not reflect risk and may leave high-risk areas unexamined.</span><span class='qd'><b>Were audited most recently</b>: recently audited areas typically carry lower residual risk and lower priority.</span><span class='qd'><b>Are requested by the IT department</b>: management requests may inform the plan but do not override an objective risk assessment.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-023","domain":1,"obj":"1A3","diff":"easy","q":"In the audit risk model, the risk that a material error exists in the absence of any related controls is called:","options":["Inherent risk","Control risk","Detection risk","Residual risk"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Inherent risk</strong> — inherent risk is the susceptibility of an area to material misstatement before considering any controls.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Control risk</b>: control risk is the risk that controls fail to prevent or detect an error, which assumes controls exist.</span><span class='qd'><b>Detection risk</b>: detection risk is the risk that the auditor's own procedures fail to catch an error.</span><span class='qd'><b>Residual risk</b>: residual risk is what remains after controls are applied, not the pre-control susceptibility.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-024","domain":1,"obj":"1A3","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor assesses inherent risk as high and control risk as high for a process. To keep overall audit risk at an acceptable level, the auditor should set detection risk to be:","options":["High, and reduce testing","Low, and expand testing","Unchanged, since it is not controllable","Zero, to eliminate all risk"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Low, and expand testing</strong> — when inherent and control risk are high, the auditor must lower detection risk by performing more extensive or precise procedures to hold audit risk at an acceptable level.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>High, and reduce testing</b>: raising detection risk when the other components are high would push overall audit risk above acceptable levels.</span><span class='qd'><b>Unchanged, since it is not controllable</b>: detection risk is precisely the component the auditor controls through the nature, timing, and extent of testing.</span><span class='qd'><b>Zero, to eliminate all risk</b>: detection risk can never be reduced to zero because testing is based on samples and judgment.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-025","domain":1,"obj":"1A3","diff":"hard","q":"The concept that determines the threshold above which an error or omission would influence the decisions of report users is:","options":["Sampling risk","Independence","Materiality","Reasonable assurance"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Materiality</strong> — materiality sets the level at which a misstatement or control weakness is significant enough to affect the decisions of those relying on the audit.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Sampling risk</b>: sampling risk is the chance that a sample is not representative of the population, a testing concept, not a significance threshold.</span><span class='qd'><b>Independence</b>: independence concerns the auditor's freedom from bias, not the significance of errors.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reasonable assurance</b>: reasonable assurance describes the confidence level of an audit, not the threshold of significance.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-026","domain":1,"obj":"1A3","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following should the IS auditor perform FIRST when planning a risk-based audit of a specific application?","options":["Draft the audit report","Select the audit sample","Hold the exit conference","Gain an understanding of the business process and its risks"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Gain an understanding of the business process and its risks</strong> — understanding the area and its risks is the foundation for scoping, assessing risk, and designing appropriate procedures.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Draft the audit report</b>: the report is produced after fieldwork and evidence gathering, not at the start.</span><span class='qd'><b>Select the audit sample</b>: sampling can only be designed after risks and controls are understood.</span><span class='qd'><b>Hold the exit conference</b>: the exit conference occurs at the end to discuss findings, not during planning.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-027","domain":1,"obj":"1A3","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is deciding how much reliance to place on a control before testing it. The MOST significant factor influencing planned reliance is the:","options":["Auditor's familiarity with the auditee staff","Number of prior audits performed by the firm","Assessed inherent and control risk of the area","Physical location of the data center"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Assessed inherent and control risk of the area</strong> — the level of assessed risk drives how much the auditor can rely on controls and therefore the nature and extent of testing.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Auditor's familiarity with the auditee staff</b>: familiarity does not objectively justify reliance and may even threaten independence.</span><span class='qd'><b>Number of prior audits performed by the firm</b>: prior audit count does not by itself determine current control reliability.</span><span class='qd'><b>Physical location of the data center</b>: location may affect logistics but not the reliance decision based on risk.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-028","domain":1,"obj":"1A3","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor is updating the audit universe. Which change would MOST likely require adding a new entry?","options":["A minor patch applied to an existing server","Deployment of a new customer-facing payment platform","A staff member changing desks","Renewal of an existing software license"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Deployment of a new customer-facing payment platform</strong> — a significant new system introduces new processes and risks that expand the population of auditable entities in the audit universe.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A minor patch applied to an existing server</b>: routine maintenance does not create a new auditable entity.</span><span class='qd'><b>A staff member changing desks</b>: a personnel move has no bearing on the inventory of auditable systems and processes.</span><span class='qd'><b>Renewal of an existing software license</b>: renewing an existing license does not introduce a new auditable area.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-029","domain":1,"obj":"1A3","diff":"medium","q":"Detection risk in the audit risk model is BEST described as the risk that:","options":["Controls fail to prevent an error","The area is inherently error-prone","The auditor's procedures fail to detect a material error","Management overrides a control"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>The auditor's procedures fail to detect a material error</strong> — detection risk reflects the possibility that the audit's own tests miss a material misstatement that controls did not prevent.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Controls fail to prevent an error</b>: that describes control risk, a separate component of the model.</span><span class='qd'><b>The area is inherently error-prone</b>: that describes inherent risk, the pre-control susceptibility.</span><span class='qd'><b>Management overrides a control</b>: management override is a specific control-risk scenario, not the definition of detection risk.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-030","domain":1,"obj":"1A3","diff":"medium","q":"The audit risk model is commonly expressed as audit risk equals:","options":["Inherent risk plus control risk plus detection risk","Inherent risk times control risk times detection risk","Inherent risk minus detection risk","Control risk divided by detection risk"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Inherent risk times control risk times detection risk</strong> — the model multiplies the three component risks, so overall audit risk is the product of inherent, control, and detection risk.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Inherent risk plus control risk plus detection risk</b>: the components are combined multiplicatively, not additively.</span><span class='qd'><b>Inherent risk minus detection risk</b>: subtraction is not how the model relates the components.</span><span class='qd'><b>Control risk divided by detection risk</b>: division does not represent the accepted audit risk relationship.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-031","domain":1,"obj":"1A4","diff":"easy","q":"A firewall configured to block unauthorized network traffic before it reaches internal systems is an example of which type of control?","options":["Detective control","Preventive control","Corrective control","Compensating control"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Preventive control</strong> — a preventive control stops an undesirable event from occurring; a firewall blocks unauthorized traffic before harm is done.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Detective control</b>: a detective control identifies an event after it has occurred, such as a log review, rather than blocking it.</span><span class='qd'><b>Corrective control</b>: a corrective control remediates after an incident, like restoring from backup, not preventing entry.</span><span class='qd'><b>Compensating control</b>: a compensating control substitutes for a missing primary control, which does not describe a standard firewall.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-032","domain":1,"obj":"1A4","diff":"medium","q":"An intrusion detection system that alerts staff after suspicious activity has occurred is primarily a:","options":["Preventive control","Corrective control","Directive control","Detective control"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Detective control</strong> — a detective control identifies and reports events after they occur; an IDS alerts on suspicious activity that has already taken place.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Preventive control</b>: a preventive control would stop the activity beforehand, which alerting does not do.</span><span class='qd'><b>Corrective control</b>: a corrective control fixes damage after detection, whereas an IDS only detects and reports.</span><span class='qd'><b>Directive control</b>: a directive control guides behavior through policy, not by detecting technical events.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-033","domain":1,"obj":"1A4","diff":"hard","q":"A data-restoration procedure that recovers files after a ransomware incident is an example of which control type?","options":["Preventive control","Detective control","Corrective control","Deterrent control"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Corrective control</strong> — a corrective control acts after an incident to restore normal operations, such as recovering data from backups after ransomware.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Preventive control</b>: prevention would stop the ransomware before impact, which restoration does not.</span><span class='qd'><b>Detective control</b>: detection identifies the incident but does not recover the files.</span><span class='qd'><b>Deterrent control</b>: a deterrent discourages an act, unlike a recovery procedure that responds after the fact.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-034","domain":1,"obj":"1A4","diff":"easy","q":"When a primary control cannot be implemented, an alternative control that provides similar risk mitigation is a:","options":["Compensating control","Detective control","Preventive control","Directive control"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Compensating control</strong> — a compensating control provides comparable assurance in place of a primary control that is impractical or too costly to implement.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Detective control</b>: detective controls identify events but are defined by function, not by substituting for a missing control.</span><span class='qd'><b>Preventive control</b>: preventive controls stop events and are not by definition substitutes for other controls.</span><span class='qd'><b>Directive control</b>: directive controls guide behavior through policy and are not alternatives to a specific primary control.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-035","domain":1,"obj":"1A4","diff":"medium","q":"Controls that apply broadly across the IT environment, such as change management and access administration, are known as:","options":["Application controls","Input controls","General controls","Output controls"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>General controls</strong> — IT general controls apply across systems and support the environment in which applications operate, covering areas like change and access management.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Application controls</b>: application controls are specific to individual transactions within one application, not the broad environment.</span><span class='qd'><b>Input controls</b>: input controls are a subset of application controls governing data entry.</span><span class='qd'><b>Output controls</b>: output controls are application controls over report generation and distribution, not environment-wide controls.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-036","domain":1,"obj":"1A4","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor notes that segregation of duties is impossible in a small team. The MOST appropriate compensating control is:","options":["Independent management review of transaction logs","Removing all access restrictions","Allowing one person to perform all tasks without review","Disabling audit logging to reduce overhead"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Independent management review of transaction logs</strong> — where duties cannot be separated, an independent supervisory review of activity logs compensates by detecting inappropriate actions.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Removing all access restrictions</b>: this weakens control further rather than compensating for a lack of separation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Allowing one person to perform all tasks without review</b>: unreviewed concentration of duties is the very risk needing mitigation, not a control.</span><span class='qd'><b>Disabling audit logging to reduce overhead</b>: removing logs eliminates the evidence needed to detect misuse.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-037","domain":1,"obj":"1A4","diff":"medium","q":"A control that validates that a transaction amount falls within an acceptable range before processing is a(n):","options":["Application input control","General control","Physical control","Corrective control"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Application input control</strong> — a range or reasonableness check is an application input control that validates data as it enters the system.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>General control</b>: general controls govern the overall environment, not the validation of individual transaction fields.</span><span class='qd'><b>Physical control</b>: physical controls protect facilities and hardware, not data field values.</span><span class='qd'><b>Corrective control</b>: a corrective control acts after an error occurs, whereas a range check prevents bad input.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-038","domain":1,"obj":"1A4","diff":"medium","q":"A statement such as \"all changes to production code are authorized and tested before deployment\" is BEST described as a:","options":["Control objective","Control activity","Control weakness","Audit finding"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Control objective</strong> — a control objective states the desired outcome that controls should achieve, such as ensuring changes are authorized and tested.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Control activity</b>: a control activity is the specific procedure performed, not the outcome it aims to achieve.</span><span class='qd'><b>Control weakness</b>: a weakness is a deficiency in controls, the opposite of a stated goal.</span><span class='qd'><b>Audit finding</b>: a finding reports a condition observed during the audit, not the objective itself.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-039","domain":1,"obj":"1A4","diff":"easy","q":"Security awareness training that instructs employees how to handle sensitive data is BEST classified as a:","options":["Detective control","Directive control","Corrective control","Compensating control"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Directive control</strong> — directive controls guide and encourage desired behavior through policies, procedures, and training.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Detective control</b>: detective controls identify events after they occur, unlike training that guides behavior beforehand.</span><span class='qd'><b>Corrective control</b>: corrective controls remediate after an incident, not instruct behavior in advance.</span><span class='qd'><b>Compensating control</b>: a compensating control substitutes for a missing control, which training does not inherently do.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-040","domain":1,"obj":"1A4","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor evaluating whether a control effectively mitigates its intended risk is assessing the control's:","options":["Cost","Popularity","Vendor reputation","Effectiveness"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Effectiveness</strong> — control effectiveness measures how well a control actually mitigates the risk it was designed to address.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Cost</b>: cost is an efficiency consideration, not a measure of whether the risk is mitigated.</span><span class='qd'><b>Popularity</b>: how commonly a control is used says nothing about its ability to mitigate the specific risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>Vendor reputation</b>: a vendor's reputation does not demonstrate that the control works as intended in this environment.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-041","domain":1,"obj":"1B1","diff":"hard","q":"Before fieldwork begins, an IS auditor should FIRST develop a document that defines the objectives, scope, timing, and resources for the engagement. This is the:","options":["Audit report","Exit conference agenda","Follow-up schedule","Audit program"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Audit program</strong> — the audit program lays out the objectives, scope, timing, and procedures for the engagement, directing the fieldwork.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Audit report</b>: the report communicates results after fieldwork, not the plan that guides it.</span><span class='qd'><b>Exit conference agenda</b>: the exit agenda structures the closing meeting, not the engagement plan.</span><span class='qd'><b>Follow-up schedule</b>: follow-up occurs after the report to verify remediation, not before fieldwork.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-042","domain":1,"obj":"1B1","diff":"easy","q":"An IS audit is falling behind schedule because a key system owner is unavailable. The audit manager's BEST first response is to:","options":["Escalate the resourcing constraint and reassess the engagement timeline","Reduce the scope silently to finish on time","Skip testing the affected area and issue the report","Assign junior staff to guess at the missing information"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Escalate the resourcing constraint and reassess the engagement timeline</strong> — good audit project management addresses obstacles by escalating and re-planning so quality and scope are preserved.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Reduce the scope silently to finish on time</b>: silently cutting scope compromises the engagement objectives and misleads stakeholders.</span><span class='qd'><b>Skip testing the affected area and issue the report</b>: omitting a planned area without disclosure leaves a material gap in assurance.</span><span class='qd'><b>Assign junior staff to guess at the missing information</b>: fabricating conclusions violates due professional care and evidence requirements.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-043","domain":1,"obj":"1B1","diff":"medium","q":"Which document records the terms, objectives, and scope agreed for a single audit engagement with the auditee?","options":["Audit charter","Audit universe","Engagement letter","Code of ethics"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Engagement letter</strong> — the engagement letter documents the agreed objectives, scope, responsibilities, and terms for a specific audit assignment.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Audit charter</b>: the charter grants the audit function's overall authority, not the terms of one engagement.</span><span class='qd'><b>Audit universe</b>: the audit universe is the inventory of auditable areas, not an agreement for a single audit.</span><span class='qd'><b>Code of ethics</b>: the code sets professional conduct expectations, not engagement-specific terms.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-044","domain":1,"obj":"1B1","diff":"hard","q":"During audit planning, the PRIMARY reason to prepare a detailed time budget for each phase is to:","options":["Enable monitoring of progress and efficient resource use","Guarantee the audit finds violations","Replace the need for supervisory review","Set the auditee's remediation deadlines"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Enable monitoring of progress and efficient resource use</strong> — a time budget lets the audit manager track progress against plan and deploy resources efficiently across phases.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Guarantee the audit finds violations</b>: a budget manages effort and cannot guarantee any particular finding.</span><span class='qd'><b>Replace the need for supervisory review</b>: supervision is a separate quality requirement not substituted by a time budget.</span><span class='qd'><b>Set the auditee's remediation deadlines</b>: remediation timelines are agreed after findings, not set by the audit time budget.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-045","domain":1,"obj":"1B1","diff":"easy","q":"Midway through fieldwork, an IS auditor identifies a significant risk area not covered by the original scope. The BEST action is to:","options":["Ignore it to stay within the approved scope","Discuss a scope change with audit management and the auditee","Immediately expand testing without informing anyone","Defer it and remove it from the workpapers"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Discuss a scope change with audit management and the auditee</strong> — a material new risk warrants a formal scope-change discussion so resources, timing, and authorization are properly adjusted.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Ignore it to stay within the approved scope</b>: ignoring a significant risk fails the auditor's professional responsibility.</span><span class='qd'><b>Immediately expand testing without informing anyone</b>: unauthorized scope expansion bypasses project governance and resource planning.</span><span class='qd'><b>Defer it and remove it from the workpapers</b>: removing evidence of a known risk from the record is improper.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-046","domain":1,"obj":"1B1","diff":"medium","q":"Assigning appropriately skilled staff to each part of an engagement is an aspect of audit project management known as:","options":["Resource management","Sampling","Reperformance","Materiality setting"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Resource management</strong> — matching staff skills to engagement tasks is a core resource-management activity that supports quality and timeliness.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Sampling</b>: sampling is a testing technique for selecting items, not staff assignment.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reperformance</b>: reperformance is an evidence-gathering procedure, unrelated to staffing decisions.</span><span class='qd'><b>Materiality setting</b>: materiality defines significance thresholds, not resource allocation.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-047","domain":1,"obj":"1B1","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor prepares workpapers that another auditor could follow to reach the same conclusions. This quality is BEST described as workpapers being:","options":["Confidential","Colorful","Sufficient and clearly documented","Written by management"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Sufficient and clearly documented</strong> — workpapers should be sufficient and clear enough that a competent reviewer can retrace the work and reach the same conclusions.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Confidential</b>: confidentiality protects the papers but does not make them reproducible or complete.</span><span class='qd'><b>Colorful</b>: appearance is irrelevant to the evidentiary and documentation quality of workpapers.</span><span class='qd'><b>Written by management</b>: workpapers must be prepared by the auditor to preserve independence.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-048","domain":1,"obj":"1B1","diff":"medium","q":"The PRIMARY purpose of supervisory review of audit workpapers during an engagement is to:","options":["Ensure objectives are met and conclusions are supported by evidence","Increase billable hours","Assign blame for delays","Reduce the auditee's remediation costs"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Ensure objectives are met and conclusions are supported by evidence</strong> — supervision confirms that the work performed meets objectives and that conclusions rest on sufficient, appropriate evidence.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Increase billable hours</b>: review is a quality control, not a mechanism to inflate hours.</span><span class='qd'><b>Assign blame for delays</b>: the goal is quality assurance, not attributing fault for schedule slips.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reduce the auditee's remediation costs</b>: remediation cost is the auditee's concern, not the purpose of workpaper review.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-049","domain":1,"obj":"1B1","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor with limited time must decide where to focus testing effort. The MOST defensible basis for allocating effort within the engagement is:","options":["Areas the auditee finds least sensitive","Alphabetical order of the systems","The relative risk and significance of each area","The order in which staff prefer to work"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>The relative risk and significance of each area</strong> — concentrating effort on higher-risk, more significant areas maximizes assurance value from limited resources.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Areas the auditee finds least sensitive</b>: auditee sensitivity is not a measure of audit risk and can bias coverage.</span><span class='qd'><b>Alphabetical order of the systems</b>: alphabetical ordering ignores risk entirely.</span><span class='qd'><b>The order in which staff prefer to work</b>: staff preference is arbitrary and unrelated to assurance priorities.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-050","domain":1,"obj":"1B1","diff":"easy","q":"A well-run audit engagement includes a kickoff meeting with the auditee PRIMARILY to:","options":["Present the final findings","Sign the audit report","Schedule the follow-up audit","Confirm scope, timing, and points of contact"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Confirm scope, timing, and points of contact</strong> — the kickoff meeting aligns both parties on scope, schedule, logistics, and communication channels before fieldwork begins.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Present the final findings</b>: findings are presented at the exit conference, not the kickoff.</span><span class='qd'><b>Sign the audit report</b>: the report is signed after fieldwork and review, not at the start.</span><span class='qd'><b>Schedule the follow-up audit</b>: follow-up is arranged after remediation commitments, not during kickoff.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-051","domain":1,"obj":"1B2","diff":"medium","q":"A sampling method in which every item in the population has a known, equal chance of selection is:","options":["Judgmental sampling","Statistical sampling","Haphazard sampling","Block sampling"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Statistical sampling</strong> — statistical sampling uses random selection so each item has a known probability of being chosen, allowing objective projection to the population.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Judgmental sampling</b>: judgmental (non-statistical) selection relies on auditor judgment, not equal probability.</span><span class='qd'><b>Haphazard sampling</b>: haphazard selection lacks a defined probability and cannot be statistically projected.</span><span class='qd'><b>Block sampling</b>: block sampling picks contiguous items, which is not equal-probability random selection.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-052","domain":1,"obj":"1B2","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor wants to estimate the rate of deviations from a control in a population. The MOST appropriate sampling approach is:","options":["Variable sampling","Attribute sampling","Monetary unit sampling","Stratified variable sampling"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Attribute sampling</strong> — attribute sampling estimates the rate of occurrence of a control deviation (a yes/no attribute) in a population, which is exactly the auditor's goal.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Variable sampling</b>: variable sampling estimates a numeric amount such as a dollar balance, not a deviation rate.</span><span class='qd'><b>Monetary unit sampling</b>: monetary unit sampling targets dollar misstatement, a variable measure, not a deviation rate.</span><span class='qd'><b>Stratified variable sampling</b>: stratification of variable sampling still estimates amounts, not the frequency of control deviations.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-053","domain":1,"obj":"1B2","diff":"easy","q":"When an IS auditor needs to estimate a monetary value or total, such as the correct dollar amount of an account, the appropriate technique is:","options":["Attribute sampling","Discovery sampling","Stop-or-go sampling","Variable sampling"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Variable sampling</strong> — variable sampling is used to estimate numeric quantities such as monetary amounts or totals in a population.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Attribute sampling</b>: attribute sampling measures the rate of a characteristic, not a monetary amount.</span><span class='qd'><b>Discovery sampling</b>: discovery sampling is aimed at finding at least one instance of a critical condition, not estimating a value.</span><span class='qd'><b>Stop-or-go sampling</b>: stop-or-go is designed to limit sample size when few errors are expected, not to estimate amounts.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-054","domain":1,"obj":"1B2","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor suspects even a single instance of fraud would be critical and wants a sample designed to reveal at least one occurrence if it exists. The BEST technique is:","options":["Discovery sampling","Variable sampling","Stratified sampling","Mean-per-unit sampling"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Discovery sampling</strong> — discovery sampling is designed to detect at least one occurrence of a critical, low-frequency condition such as fraud when finding even one is important.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Variable sampling</b>: variable sampling estimates amounts and is not optimized to reveal a single critical instance.</span><span class='qd'><b>Stratified sampling</b>: stratification improves precision across subgroups but is not specifically aimed at finding one critical case.</span><span class='qd'><b>Mean-per-unit sampling</b>: mean-per-unit is a variable-estimation method for values, not for discovering a rare event.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-055","domain":1,"obj":"1B2","diff":"hard","q":"Stop-or-go sampling is used PRIMARILY to:","options":["Guarantee the entire population is tested","Estimate monetary misstatement","Eliminate sampling risk entirely","Minimize sample size when the expected error rate is low"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Minimize sample size when the expected error rate is low</strong> — stop-or-go sampling allows the auditor to stop early when few errors appear, reducing unnecessary testing.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Guarantee the entire population is tested</b>: testing the whole population would not be sampling at all.</span><span class='qd'><b>Estimate monetary misstatement</b>: estimating dollar amounts is the purpose of variable sampling, not stop-or-go.</span><span class='qd'><b>Eliminate sampling risk entirely</b>: no sampling method eliminates sampling risk completely.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-056","domain":1,"obj":"1B2","diff":"medium","q":"The risk that an IS auditor concludes controls are effective when in fact they are not, based on the sample examined, is:","options":["The risk of incorrect rejection","Nonsampling risk","The risk of incorrect acceptance","Inherent risk"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>The risk of incorrect acceptance</strong> — this sampling risk (also called beta risk) occurs when the sample suggests controls are effective though they are not, undermining audit effectiveness.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The risk of incorrect rejection</b>: incorrect rejection (alpha risk) concludes controls are ineffective when they actually work, affecting efficiency not effectiveness.</span><span class='qd'><b>Nonsampling risk</b>: nonsampling risk arises from human error or poor procedures, not from the sample being unrepresentative.</span><span class='qd'><b>Inherent risk</b>: inherent risk is the pre-control susceptibility of an area, unrelated to sample conclusions.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-057","domain":1,"obj":"1B2","diff":"medium","q":"Sampling risk is BEST defined as the risk that:","options":["The auditor uses the wrong audit software","The sample is not representative of the whole population","The auditee refuses to cooperate","The report is issued late"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>The sample is not representative of the whole population</strong> — sampling risk is the chance that conclusions drawn from a sample differ from those that testing the entire population would yield.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The auditor uses the wrong audit software</b>: tool errors are nonsampling risk, not sampling risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>The auditee refuses to cooperate</b>: cooperation issues are scope limitations, not sampling risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>The report is issued late</b>: timing of the report is a project matter, unrelated to sampling representativeness.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-058","domain":1,"obj":"1B2","diff":"easy","q":"Non-statistical (judgmental) sampling differs from statistical sampling in that non-statistical sampling:","options":["Always uses a larger sample","Guarantees no sampling risk","Requires specialized software","Does not permit objective mathematical projection of results"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Does not permit objective mathematical projection of results</strong> — because selection is based on judgment rather than probability, non-statistical sampling cannot be projected to the population with measurable confidence.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Always uses a larger sample</b>: sample size depends on the situation, not on whether the method is statistical.</span><span class='qd'><b>Guarantees no sampling risk</b>: all sampling carries sampling risk regardless of the method.</span><span class='qd'><b>Requires specialized software</b>: judgmental sampling can be done manually and does not require special tools.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-059","domain":1,"obj":"1B2","diff":"medium","q":"Increasing the sample size in an attribute sampling test will generally:","options":["Decrease sampling risk","Increase sampling risk","Have no effect on sampling risk","Eliminate nonsampling risk"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Decrease sampling risk</strong> — a larger, well-selected sample is more representative of the population, reducing the risk that the sample leads to a wrong conclusion.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Increase sampling risk</b>: a larger sample lowers rather than raises sampling risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>Have no effect on sampling risk</b>: sample size is a primary driver of sampling risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>Eliminate nonsampling risk</b>: nonsampling risk stems from procedural or human error and is not addressed by sample size.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-060","domain":1,"obj":"1B2","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor sets the tolerable deviation rate at 5% and the expected population deviation rate at 4%. The narrow gap between them will MOST likely require:","options":["A very small sample","No sample at all","A larger sample size","Only judgmental selection"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>A larger sample size</strong> — a small margin between the tolerable and expected deviation rates demands a larger sample to distinguish acceptable from unacceptable control performance with confidence.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A very small sample</b>: a small sample would lack the precision needed to resolve such a narrow gap.</span><span class='qd'><b>No sample at all</b>: skipping sampling provides no evidence about the deviation rate.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only judgmental selection</b>: judgmental selection does not address the precision required by the narrow rate gap.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-061","domain":1,"obj":"1B3","diff":"easy","q":"For audit evidence to be useful, it must be sufficient, reliable, and:","options":["Relevant to the audit objective","Colorful","Provided only by management","Kept secret from reviewers"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Relevant to the audit objective</strong> — evidence must relate directly to the objective and assertion being tested, in addition to being sufficient and reliable.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Colorful</b>: presentation appearance has no bearing on evidential quality.</span><span class='qd'><b>Provided only by management</b>: management-provided evidence is generally less reliable than independent evidence.</span><span class='qd'><b>Kept secret from reviewers</b>: evidence must be available for supervisory review, not hidden.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-062","domain":1,"obj":"1B3","diff":"medium","q":"Which of the following typically provides the MOST reliable audit evidence?","options":["A verbal statement from the process owner","A photocopy provided by the auditee","An undocumented recollection of a past control","Evidence obtained directly by the auditor through reperformance"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Evidence obtained directly by the auditor through reperformance</strong> — evidence the auditor generates independently is the most reliable because it does not depend on the auditee's assertions.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A verbal statement from the process owner</b>: oral representations are weak evidence and must be corroborated.</span><span class='qd'><b>A photocopy provided by the auditee</b>: auditee-supplied copies are less reliable and can be altered.</span><span class='qd'><b>An undocumented recollection of a past control</b>: unrecorded recollections are unreliable and unverifiable.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-063","domain":1,"obj":"1B3","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor watches an operator perform the daily backup to confirm the procedure is followed. This evidence-gathering technique is:","options":["Observation","Inquiry","Reperformance","Confirmation"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Observation</strong> — observation involves watching a process or procedure being performed to gather evidence about how it operates.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Inquiry</b>: inquiry means asking questions of personnel, not watching the activity.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reperformance</b>: reperformance means the auditor independently re-executes the control, not merely watching it.</span><span class='qd'><b>Confirmation</b>: confirmation obtains verification from a third party, which is not observing an operator.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-064","domain":1,"obj":"1B3","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor relies solely on observation of a control at one point in time. The MAIN limitation of this evidence is that:","options":["It is always inadmissible","Personnel may behave differently while being watched","It requires expensive software","It cannot be documented"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Personnel may behave differently while being watched</strong> — observation captures only a moment and can be biased because staff often follow procedures more carefully when they know they are being observed.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It is always inadmissible</b>: observation is valid evidence, though limited; it is not inadmissible.</span><span class='qd'><b>It requires expensive software</b>: observation needs no special tools, so cost is not its limitation.</span><span class='qd'><b>It cannot be documented</b>: observations can and should be documented in workpapers.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-065","domain":1,"obj":"1B3","diff":"medium","q":"Computer-assisted audit techniques (CAATs) are MOST valuable to an IS auditor because they:","options":["Remove the need for any audit judgment","Guarantee no errors exist","Replace the audit charter","Allow analysis of entire large data populations rather than small samples"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Allow analysis of entire large data populations rather than small samples</strong> — CAATs let the auditor test 100% of transactions in large datasets, increasing coverage and confidence.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Remove the need for any audit judgment</b>: CAATs support judgment but do not replace the auditor's interpretation of results.</span><span class='qd'><b>Guarantee no errors exist</b>: no technique guarantees error-free populations; CAATs find issues, not certainty.</span><span class='qd'><b>Replace the audit charter</b>: CAATs are analysis tools unrelated to the function's authorizing charter.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-066","domain":1,"obj":"1B3","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor recalculates payroll deductions independently to verify the system's output. This procedure is:","options":["Reperformance","Inquiry","Observation","Inspection"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Reperformance</strong> — reperformance means the auditor independently re-executes a calculation or control to verify the result produced by the system.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Inquiry</b>: inquiry is asking questions, not recomputing values.</span><span class='qd'><b>Observation</b>: observation is watching an activity, not independently redoing it.</span><span class='qd'><b>Inspection</b>: inspection examines documents or records but does not re-execute the calculation.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-067","domain":1,"obj":"1B3","diff":"medium","q":"Continuous auditing is BEST described as an approach that:","options":["Audits only once every several years","Eliminates the need for an audit charter","Uses automated tools to test controls and transactions on a near-real-time basis","Relies exclusively on management inquiry"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Uses automated tools to test controls and transactions on a near-real-time basis</strong> — continuous auditing embeds automated checks that evaluate controls and data frequently, enabling timely detection of issues.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Audits only once every several years</b>: infrequent auditing is the opposite of a continuous approach.</span><span class='qd'><b>Eliminates the need for an audit charter</b>: the charter still authorizes the function regardless of technique.</span><span class='qd'><b>Relies exclusively on management inquiry</b>: continuous auditing relies on automated data analysis, not solely on inquiry.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-068","domain":1,"obj":"1B3","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor must choose between examining an original signed contract and a scanned copy emailed by the auditee. To maximize evidence reliability, the auditor should:","options":["Prefer the scanned copy for convenience","Rely on the auditee's verbal summary","Examine the original signed contract","Accept whichever arrives first"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Examine the original signed contract</strong> — original documents are more reliable than copies because copies can be altered and lack the assurance of an unmodified source.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Prefer the scanned copy for convenience</b>: convenience does not justify accepting weaker, alterable evidence.</span><span class='qd'><b>Rely on the auditee's verbal summary</b>: a verbal summary is the least reliable form of evidence.</span><span class='qd'><b>Accept whichever arrives first</b>: timing of arrival is irrelevant to evidential reliability.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-069","domain":1,"obj":"1B3","diff":"easy","q":"Confirming an account balance directly with an external bank rather than accepting the client's ledger is preferred because externally sourced evidence is generally:","options":["Cheaper to obtain","Always required by law","Less relevant to the objective","More reliable due to its independent origin"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>More reliable due to its independent origin</strong> — evidence from an independent external party is more reliable because it is not under the auditee's control and is harder to manipulate.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Cheaper to obtain</b>: external confirmations often cost more effort, so cost is not the reason.</span><span class='qd'><b>Always required by law</b>: confirmation is a professional preference for reliability, not a universal legal mandate.</span><span class='qd'><b>Less relevant to the objective</b>: independent confirmation is highly relevant to verifying the balance, not less so.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-070","domain":1,"obj":"1B3","diff":"medium","q":"Asking system administrators about how access is granted, without other corroboration, is an example of which evidence technique?","options":["Inquiry","Reperformance","Inspection","Recalculation"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Inquiry</strong> — inquiry is obtaining information by asking questions of knowledgeable personnel; on its own it is relatively weak and needs corroboration.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Reperformance</b>: reperformance independently re-executes a control rather than asking about it.</span><span class='qd'><b>Inspection</b>: inspection examines records or documents, not verbal responses.</span><span class='qd'><b>Recalculation</b>: recalculation checks the mathematical accuracy of figures, unrelated to asking questions.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-071","domain":1,"obj":"1B4","diff":"hard","q":"Audit data analytics MOST directly help an IS auditor by enabling the auditor to:","options":["Avoid documenting any findings","Eliminate the need for professional judgment","Skip the planning phase","Examine full data populations to identify anomalies and patterns"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Examine full data populations to identify anomalies and patterns</strong> — data analytics let the auditor analyze complete datasets to surface outliers, trends, and exceptions that targeted testing might miss.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Avoid documenting any findings</b>: analytics generate findings that still must be documented.</span><span class='qd'><b>Eliminate the need for professional judgment</b>: interpreting analytic results still requires auditor judgment.</span><span class='qd'><b>Skip the planning phase</b>: analytics support, but do not replace, sound audit planning.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-072","domain":1,"obj":"1B4","diff":"easy","q":"Before drawing conclusions from a data analytics routine, the IS auditor should FIRST validate the:","options":["Completeness and integrity of the source data","Color scheme of the dashboard","Auditee's opinion of the results","Vendor's marketing claims"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Completeness and integrity of the source data</strong> — conclusions are only as good as the data; the auditor must confirm the data is complete and unaltered before relying on analytic output.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Color scheme of the dashboard</b>: presentation styling has no effect on the validity of the analysis.</span><span class='qd'><b>Auditee's opinion of the results</b>: the auditee's view does not establish data reliability and could bias conclusions.</span><span class='qd'><b>Vendor's marketing claims</b>: vendor claims do not verify the integrity of the actual data analyzed.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-073","domain":1,"obj":"1B4","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor uses analytics to flag transactions that occurred outside normal business hours. This is an example of:","options":["Anomaly (exception) detection","Predictive modeling","Sentiment analysis","Data encryption"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Anomaly (exception) detection</strong> — identifying transactions that deviate from expected norms, such as off-hours activity, is a classic anomaly-detection use of audit analytics.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Predictive modeling</b>: predictive modeling forecasts future outcomes rather than flagging current exceptions.</span><span class='qd'><b>Sentiment analysis</b>: sentiment analysis evaluates opinion in text, not transaction timing.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data encryption</b>: encryption protects data confidentiality and is not an analytic detection method.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-074","domain":1,"obj":"1B4","diff":"easy","q":"When an IS auditor obtains a large extract of production data for analytics, the BEST way to confirm the extract is reliable is to:","options":["Assume it is correct because IT provided it","Delete records that look unusual","Reconcile record counts and control totals to the source system","Rely on the file name for assurance"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Reconcile record counts and control totals to the source system</strong> — reconciling counts and totals to the source verifies that the extract is complete and accurate before analysis begins.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Assume it is correct because IT provided it</b>: source of the file does not by itself prove completeness or accuracy.</span><span class='qd'><b>Delete records that look unusual</b>: removing records destroys the very anomalies the analysis should investigate.</span><span class='qd'><b>Rely on the file name for assurance</b>: a file name provides no evidence of data integrity.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-075","domain":1,"obj":"1B4","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor building repeatable analytics scripts to run each quarter is MOST directly enabling:","options":["A one-time forensic seizure","Elimination of the audit committee","Continuous or recurring automated auditing","Manual re-keying of data"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Continuous or recurring automated auditing</strong> — reusable, scheduled analytics scripts support continuous auditing by re-testing controls and data on a recurring basis.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A one-time forensic seizure</b>: recurring scripts are the opposite of a single forensic event.</span><span class='qd'><b>Elimination of the audit committee</b>: analytics do not remove governance bodies.</span><span class='qd'><b>Manual re-keying of data</b>: automation reduces manual re-keying rather than enabling it.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-076","domain":1,"obj":"1B4","diff":"hard","q":"Which of the following BEST describes a benefit of using data analytics over traditional sampling?","options":["It guarantees zero errors","It can test 100% of the population instead of a sample","It removes the need for evidence","It always costs nothing"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>It can test 100% of the population instead of a sample</strong> — analytics can examine an entire population, increasing coverage compared with testing only a sample.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It guarantees zero errors</b>: analyzing all data reveals issues but cannot guarantee an error-free population.</span><span class='qd'><b>It removes the need for evidence</b>: analytic results are themselves evidence that must be evaluated and retained.</span><span class='qd'><b>It always costs nothing</b>: analytics require tools, skills, and effort, so they are not free.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-077","domain":1,"obj":"1B4","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor finds that an analytics routine flagged thousands of exceptions. The MOST appropriate next step is to:","options":["Refine the criteria and investigate exceptions to distinguish true issues from false positives","Report all exceptions as confirmed findings immediately","Discard the analysis as unusable","Ask the auditee to define what counts as an exception"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Refine the criteria and investigate exceptions to distinguish true issues from false positives</strong> — a high exception count usually includes false positives, so the auditor must refine logic and investigate before concluding.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Report all exceptions as confirmed findings immediately</b>: unvalidated exceptions may be false positives and reporting them as findings would be inaccurate.</span><span class='qd'><b>Discard the analysis as unusable</b>: a large result set is a starting point for refinement, not grounds to abandon the analysis.</span><span class='qd'><b>Ask the auditee to define what counts as an exception</b>: letting the auditee set the exception criteria would impair objectivity.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-078","domain":1,"obj":"1B4","diff":"medium","q":"For audit data analytics to be repeatable and defensible, the IS auditor should MOST importantly:","options":["Keep the methodology secret","Document the data sources, logic, and steps used","Change the logic each run without notes","Use only spreadsheets that overwrite prior work"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Document the data sources, logic, and steps used</strong> — documenting sources and procedures makes the analysis reproducible, reviewable, and defensible if challenged.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Keep the methodology secret</b>: hidden methodology prevents review and undermines defensibility.</span><span class='qd'><b>Change the logic each run without notes</b>: undocumented changes make results irreproducible.</span><span class='qd'><b>Use only spreadsheets that overwrite prior work</b>: overwriting destroys the audit trail needed to defend conclusions.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-079","domain":1,"obj":"1B4","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor wants to detect duplicate vendor payments across a large accounts-payable file. The MOST efficient technique is to:","options":["Manually eyeball a printed report","Ask each clerk if duplicates occurred","Test a small judgmental sample only","Run a data analytics routine to match on vendor, amount, and date"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Run a data analytics routine to match on vendor, amount, and date</strong> — automated matching across the full file efficiently identifies duplicate payments that manual review would likely miss.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Manually eyeball a printed report</b>: manual review of a large file is slow and unreliable for finding duplicates.</span><span class='qd'><b>Ask each clerk if duplicates occurred</b>: inquiry alone provides weak, unverified evidence.</span><span class='qd'><b>Test a small judgmental sample only</b>: a small sample would miss most duplicates spread across the population.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-080","domain":1,"obj":"1B4","diff":"easy","q":"Visualizing audit analytics results in charts and dashboards PRIMARILY helps the auditor to:","options":["Communicate patterns and outliers to stakeholders more clearly","Encrypt the data","Eliminate the need to gather evidence","Prevent the auditee from responding"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Communicate patterns and outliers to stakeholders more clearly</strong> — visualization makes complex analytic results easier for stakeholders to understand and act upon.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Encrypt the data</b>: visualization presents results and does not provide encryption.</span><span class='qd'><b>Eliminate the need to gather evidence</b>: charts summarize evidence but do not replace collecting it.</span><span class='qd'><b>Prevent the auditee from responding</b>: reporting results should invite, not block, auditee response.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-081","domain":1,"obj":"1B5","diff":"medium","q":"An audit finding is MOST completely described when it includes the condition, criteria, cause, and:","options":["The effect (impact) and a recommendation","The auditor's salary","The auditee's lunch schedule","A list of unrelated systems"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>The effect (impact) and a recommendation</strong> — a well-structured finding presents condition, criteria, cause, effect, and a recommendation so the reader understands the issue and how to address it.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The auditor's salary</b>: the auditor's pay is irrelevant to a finding.</span><span class='qd'><b>The auditee's lunch schedule</b>: unrelated operational trivia does not belong in a finding.</span><span class='qd'><b>A list of unrelated systems</b>: irrelevant systems add noise, not the required effect and recommendation.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-082","domain":1,"obj":"1B5","diff":"hard","q":"The PRIMARY purpose of the exit conference (closing meeting) with the auditee is to:","options":["Assign disciplinary action to staff","Renew the audit charter","Select the next audit sample","Validate findings for accuracy and discuss management responses before the report is finalized"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Validate findings for accuracy and discuss management responses before the report is finalized</strong> — the exit conference confirms factual accuracy and gathers management's responses, strengthening the report's credibility.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Assign disciplinary action to staff</b>: discipline is management's responsibility, not the purpose of the exit conference.</span><span class='qd'><b>Renew the audit charter</b>: the charter is a governance document unrelated to a single engagement's closing meeting.</span><span class='qd'><b>Select the next audit sample</b>: sampling is a fieldwork activity, not part of the exit conference.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-083","domain":1,"obj":"1B5","diff":"medium","q":"When the auditee disagrees with a finding but the IS auditor is confident it is supported by evidence, the auditor should:","options":["Remove the finding to avoid conflict","Change the conclusion to match the auditee","Delay the report indefinitely","Retain the finding and include the auditee's response in the report"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Retain the finding and include the auditee's response in the report</strong> — a well-supported finding should stand, with the auditee's differing view documented so readers see both positions.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Remove the finding to avoid conflict</b>: deleting a substantiated finding compromises the integrity of the report.</span><span class='qd'><b>Change the conclusion to match the auditee</b>: altering evidence-based conclusions to satisfy the auditee impairs objectivity.</span><span class='qd'><b>Delay the report indefinitely</b>: indefinite delay withholds important information from stakeholders.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-084","domain":1,"obj":"1B5","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is finalizing an opinion but has been unable to obtain evidence over a material portion of the scope. The MOST appropriate reporting outcome is to:","options":["Issue an unqualified (clean) opinion","Issue a qualified opinion or scope limitation disclosure","State that all controls are effective","Omit any mention of the missing evidence"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Issue a qualified opinion or scope limitation disclosure</strong> — when a material area could not be examined, the auditor must qualify the opinion or disclose the scope limitation so users understand its bounds.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Issue an unqualified (clean) opinion</b>: a clean opinion is not supportable when material evidence is missing.</span><span class='qd'><b>State that all controls are effective</b>: asserting effectiveness without evidence would be misleading.</span><span class='qd'><b>Omit any mention of the missing evidence</b>: concealing the scope limitation deceives report users.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-085","domain":1,"obj":"1B5","diff":"easy","q":"Audit follow-up procedures are performed PRIMARILY to:","options":["Start a completely new audit universe","Change the audit charter","Determine whether management has implemented agreed corrective actions","Recompute the original sample"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Determine whether management has implemented agreed corrective actions</strong> — follow-up verifies that management has acted on findings and that risks have been adequately remediated.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Start a completely new audit universe</b>: rebuilding the audit universe is a planning activity, not follow-up.</span><span class='qd'><b>Change the audit charter</b>: follow-up does not alter the function's authorizing charter.</span><span class='qd'><b>Recompute the original sample</b>: follow-up checks remediation status, not re-running the earlier sample.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-086","domain":1,"obj":"1B5","diff":"medium","q":"To be most useful, an audit report's recommendations should be:","options":["Actionable, specific, and tied to the identified risk","Vague so management has flexibility","Written only in technical jargon","Focused on blaming individuals"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Actionable, specific, and tied to the identified risk</strong> — effective recommendations clearly state what should be done to address the risk, enabling management to act.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Vague so management has flexibility</b>: vague recommendations leave management unsure how to remediate.</span><span class='qd'><b>Written only in technical jargon</b>: jargon-heavy text hinders understanding by decision-makers.</span><span class='qd'><b>Focused on blaming individuals</b>: recommendations should address controls and risk, not attribute blame.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-087","domain":1,"obj":"1B5","diff":"hard","q":"After issuing a report, the IS auditor learns management accepted the risk of a significant finding rather than remediating it. The auditor should:","options":["Force management to remediate","Document management's formal risk acceptance and, if the residual risk is unacceptable, escalate to those charged with governance","Delete the finding from the record","Take no further action and close the file"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Document management's formal risk acceptance and, if the residual risk is unacceptable, escalate to those charged with governance</strong> — the auditor records the acceptance and escalates when the residual risk exceeds acceptable levels.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Force management to remediate</b>: the auditor advises but cannot compel management action.</span><span class='qd'><b>Delete the finding from the record</b>: removing a valid finding destroys the audit trail and misleads stakeholders.</span><span class='qd'><b>Take no further action and close the file</b>: ignoring an unacceptable residual risk fails the auditor's duty to escalate.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-088","domain":1,"obj":"1B5","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor should communicate a critical control weakness that poses immediate risk:","options":["Only in the final report months later","Promptly to appropriate management rather than waiting for the final report","Never, to avoid alarming staff","Only after the follow-up audit"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Promptly to appropriate management rather than waiting for the final report</strong> — urgent, high-risk issues should be reported immediately so management can act before the formal report is issued.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Only in the final report months later</b>: delaying a critical warning allows harm to continue.</span><span class='qd'><b>Never, to avoid alarming staff</b>: withholding a serious risk is a dereliction of the reporting duty.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only after the follow-up audit</b>: waiting for follow-up needlessly postpones urgent remediation.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-089","domain":1,"obj":"1B5","diff":"medium","q":"When rating the severity of findings in a report, the IS auditor should prioritize them based on:","options":["Their risk and potential business impact","The order they were discovered","The length of their description","How the auditee feels about them"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Their risk and potential business impact</strong> — prioritizing findings by risk and impact directs management attention to the most consequential issues first.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The order they were discovered</b>: discovery order does not reflect the importance of a finding.</span><span class='qd'><b>The length of their description</b>: the amount of text says nothing about severity.</span><span class='qd'><b>How the auditee feels about them</b>: auditee sentiment is not an objective basis for severity ranking.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-090","domain":1,"obj":"1B5","diff":"hard","q":"An audit opinion that states, without reservation, that controls are suitably designed and operating effectively is a(n):","options":["Adverse opinion","Disclaimer of opinion","Unqualified (unmodified) opinion","Qualified opinion"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Unqualified (unmodified) opinion</strong> — an unqualified opinion expresses, without reservation, that controls are suitably designed and operating effectively.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Adverse opinion</b>: an adverse opinion states that controls are not effective, the opposite conclusion.</span><span class='qd'><b>Disclaimer of opinion</b>: a disclaimer means the auditor cannot form an opinion at all.</span><span class='qd'><b>Qualified opinion</b>: a qualified opinion includes an exception, so it is not without reservation.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-091","domain":1,"obj":"1B6","diff":"medium","q":"A program that continuously evaluates and improves the quality of the internal audit activity is known as a:","options":["Business impact analysis","Disaster recovery plan","Change advisory board","Quality assurance and improvement program (QAIP)"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Quality assurance and improvement program (QAIP)</strong> — a QAIP includes ongoing and periodic assessments to ensure the audit activity conforms to standards and continually improves.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Business impact analysis</b>: a BIA assesses disruption impacts, not audit quality.</span><span class='qd'><b>Disaster recovery plan</b>: a DR plan restores systems after disruption, unrelated to audit quality.</span><span class='qd'><b>Change advisory board</b>: a CAB reviews IT changes, not the quality of the audit function.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-092","domain":1,"obj":"1B6","diff":"medium","q":"An external quality assessment of an internal audit function should MOST appropriately be performed by:","options":["The audit team leader who ran the engagements","The CIO whose area was audited","A qualified, independent reviewer from outside the organization","A junior auditor within the same team"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>A qualified, independent reviewer from outside the organization</strong> — an external assessment requires an independent, competent reviewer to provide an objective evaluation of the audit function.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The audit team leader who ran the engagements</b>: reviewing one's own work is not independent.</span><span class='qd'><b>The CIO whose area was audited</b>: the CIO is an auditee stakeholder and cannot objectively assess the audit function.</span><span class='qd'><b>A junior auditor within the same team</b>: an internal team member lacks the independence required for an external assessment.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-093","domain":1,"obj":"1B6","diff":"easy","q":"Ongoing internal monitoring within a QAIP MOST directly helps the audit function by:","options":["Replacing the need for external assessments entirely","Setting the organization's risk appetite","Providing continuous feedback on conformance and performance of engagements","Approving the annual financial statements"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Providing continuous feedback on conformance and performance of engagements</strong> — internal monitoring gives real-time feedback so the audit function can correct issues and improve continuously.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Replacing the need for external assessments entirely</b>: internal monitoring complements but does not replace periodic external assessments.</span><span class='qd'><b>Setting the organization's risk appetite</b>: risk appetite is set by governance, not by audit's quality monitoring.</span><span class='qd'><b>Approving the annual financial statements</b>: statement approval is a management and board function, not part of a QAIP.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-094","domain":1,"obj":"1B6","diff":"medium","q":"A periodic internal QAIP review finds that several engagements lacked evidence of supervisory review. The BEST corrective action is to:","options":["Ignore it since the reports were already issued","Strengthen and enforce the supervisory review process going forward","Stop performing audits entirely","Blame individual auditors publicly"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Strengthen and enforce the supervisory review process going forward</strong> — the purpose of a QAIP is continual improvement, so the function should reinforce the review process to prevent recurrence.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Ignore it since the reports were already issued</b>: ignoring a systemic gap allows the quality weakness to persist.</span><span class='qd'><b>Stop performing audits entirely</b>: halting the function is an overreaction that abandons its mission rather than improving it.</span><span class='qd'><b>Blame individual auditors publicly</b>: public blame does not fix the process weakness and harms the team.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-095","domain":1,"obj":"1B6","diff":"hard","q":"Which of the following BEST demonstrates that the IS audit function conforms with professional standards?","options":["A high number of findings per audit","Documented results of internal and external quality assessments","The size of the audit budget","The seniority of the audit staff"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Documented results of internal and external quality assessments</strong> — quality assessment results provide objective evidence of conformance with professional standards.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A high number of findings per audit</b>: finding volume does not indicate standards conformance and may reflect scope rather than quality.</span><span class='qd'><b>The size of the audit budget</b>: budget size does not demonstrate that standards are followed.</span><span class='qd'><b>The seniority of the audit staff</b>: experienced staff help, but seniority alone is not evidence of conformance.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-096","domain":1,"obj":"1B6","diff":"easy","q":"Collecting metrics such as engagement cycle time and client satisfaction supports the QAIP by:","options":["Replacing the audit charter","Measuring audit performance to drive improvement","Eliminating the need for evidence","Setting employee bonuses only"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Measuring audit performance to drive improvement</strong> — performance metrics let the function assess how well it operates and identify where to improve.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Replacing the audit charter</b>: metrics inform improvement but do not replace the authorizing charter.</span><span class='qd'><b>Eliminating the need for evidence</b>: metrics are about function performance, not a substitute for engagement evidence.</span><span class='qd'><b>Setting employee bonuses only</b>: metrics serve improvement broadly, not solely compensation decisions.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-097","domain":1,"obj":"1B6","diff":"medium","q":"An IS audit manager wants assurance that the function is free from bias in selecting engagements. The QAIP element that BEST addresses this is:","options":["A larger travel budget","More frequent staff meetings","Independent review of the risk-based planning methodology","A faster reporting template"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Independent review of the risk-based planning methodology</strong> — independently reviewing how engagements are selected verifies that planning is objective and risk-driven rather than biased.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A larger travel budget</b>: budget size has no bearing on objectivity of engagement selection.</span><span class='qd'><b>More frequent staff meetings</b>: meeting frequency does not verify the impartiality of planning.</span><span class='qd'><b>A faster reporting template</b>: report speed is unrelated to whether selection is unbiased.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-098","domain":1,"obj":"1B6","diff":"hard","q":"The results of QAIP assessments should be communicated PRIMARILY to:","options":["Only the audit staff involved","The organization's external customers","No one, to keep them confidential","Senior management and the audit committee or board"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Senior management and the audit committee or board</strong> — QAIP results should be reported to senior management and the board so governance can assess the audit function's quality and independence.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Only the audit staff involved</b>: limiting results to staff withholds them from the governance bodies that need them.</span><span class='qd'><b>The organization's external customers</b>: customers are not the intended recipients of internal quality assessments.</span><span class='qd'><b>No one, to keep them confidential</b>: withholding results defeats the accountability purpose of the QAIP.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-099","domain":1,"obj":"1B6","diff":"easy","q":"Incorporating lessons learned from completed engagements into future audit methodology is an example of:","options":["A scope limitation","A conflict of interest","A sampling technique","Continuous improvement of the audit process"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Continuous improvement of the audit process</strong> — feeding lessons learned back into methodology is a core continuous-improvement practice within a QAIP.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A scope limitation</b>: a scope limitation restricts an engagement, unrelated to improving methodology.</span><span class='qd'><b>A conflict of interest</b>: applying lessons learned does not create a conflict of interest.</span><span class='qd'><b>A sampling technique</b>: lessons learned inform process improvement, not item selection for testing.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-100","domain":1,"obj":"1B6","diff":"medium","q":"External quality assessments of an internal audit function are generally expected to be performed at least:","options":["Once every five years by a qualified independent party","Every month","Only when a finding is disputed","Never, if internal monitoring exists"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Once every five years by a qualified independent party</strong> — professional guidance calls for an external quality assessment at least once every five years, conducted by a qualified, independent reviewer.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Every month</b>: monthly external assessments are impractical and far more frequent than expected.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only when a finding is disputed</b>: external assessments are scheduled periodically, not triggered solely by disputes.</span><span class='qd'><b>Never, if internal monitoring exists</b>: internal monitoring does not replace the required periodic external assessment.</span>"}
]);
